'''Timothy Duane "Tim" Hardaway, Jr.''' (born March 16, 1992) is an American [[shooting guard]] who was drafted by the New York Knicks in the [[2013 NBA Draft]]. He previously played [[college basketball]] for the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines]] and declared for the [[NBA Draft]] after completing his junior season for the [[2012<U+2013>13 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2012<U+2013>13 team]]. He is the son of [[National Basketball Association]] [[NBA All-Star Game|All-Star]] [[Tim Hardaway]]. As a [[high school basketball]] player, he was a three-time All-City performer for [[Miami Palmetto High School]].

As a freshman during the [[2010<U+2013>11 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]], earned four [[Big Ten Conference]] Freshman of the Week awards, including three in the final four weeks during which he averaged over 20 [[point (basketball)|points]] a game to help the [[2010<U+2013>11 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2010<U+2013>11 team]] to climb up to fourth in the [[2010<U+2013>11 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season]] standings. He was an honorable mention All-Big Ten selection and a unanimous Big Ten All-Freshman team selection following the season. He established the Michigan freshman record for single-season three-point shots made. He was a 2011 [[Collegeinsider.com]] Freshmen All-America selection and participated as a member of Team USA in the [[2011 FIBA Under-19 World Championship]].  As a sophomore for the [[2011<U+2013>12 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2011<U+2013>12 team]], he earned the [[2011<U+2013>12 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|2011<U+2013>12 All-Big Ten]] 3rd team recognition. He earned [[2012<U+2013>13 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|2012<U+2013>13 All-Big Ten]] (1st team: coaches and 2nd team: media) recognition.

==High School==
Hardaway, who is the son of Yolanda and NBA All-Star [[Tim Hardaway]],<ref name=10TH/> spent his freshman year at [[Palmer Trinity School]] before transferring to [[Miami Palmetto High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/while-creating-his-own-game-michigan-freshman-guard-tim-hardaway-jr-has-shades-of-his-father/|title=Michigan freshman guard Tim Hardaway Jr. has shades of his father's game|accessdate=2011-02-28|date=2010-08-22|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref> As a freshman, he played [[high school football]] for a year before focusing on basketball.<ref name=TSoaN>{{cite web|url=http://www.michigandaily.com/sports/shadow-name-how-tim-hardaway-jr-has-formed-his-basketball-identity?page=0,4|title=The Shadow of a Name: How Tim Hardaway Jr. has formed his basketball identity|accessdate=2012-01-28|date=2011-10-30|work=[[Michigan Daily]]|author=Estes, Ben}}</ref>  As he focused on basketball, he had a tumultuous relationship with his father, who acted like a second coach, and was overlooked by most [[college basketball]] programs.<ref name=TSoaN/> Michigan was the first school to contact him, communicating by mail during his sophomore year.<ref name=TSoaN/> During his junior year, Michigan [[head coach]] [[John Beilein]] invited him on an unofficial visit to watch [[2008<U+2013>09 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]] play #4 [[2008<U+2013>09 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]] on December 6 to see unranked Michigan pull an upset.<ref name=TSoaN/> The 81&ndash;73 victory was an important win for the program.<ref name=Ssc2aMlDoe>{{vcite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=283410130|title=Sims scores career-high 28 as Michigan limits Duke's outside effectiveness|accessdate=December 06, 2008|date=December 06, 2008|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|work=[[ESPN.com]]}}</ref> In the summer before his senior season, he attended Beilein<U+2019>s Elite Camp in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]], receiving an offer that he accepted.  At the time, Hardaway was unranked in the [[Rivals.com]] Top-150 and his only other offers were from [[Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball|Minnesota]] and [[Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball|Kansas State]].<ref name=TSoaN/> He was a first team All-City selection in 2009 and 2010 after being a third team selection in 2008.  During his 2009&ndash;10 senior season, he averaged 31.7 points, 7.3 [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] and 4.0 [[assist (basketball)|assists]].<ref name=10TH>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/hardawayjr_tim00.html|title=10 Tim Hardaway Jr.|accessdate=2011-02-27|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> In the Florida state championships against [[Pine Crest School]], he posted 42 points against [[Brandon Knight (basketball)|Brandon Knight]] who had 36.<ref name=TSoaN/>  [[ESPN]] rated him as the 93rd best player and 28th best shooting guard in the class of 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/66934|title=Tim Hardaway, Jr.|accessdate=2011-02-27|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  [[Scout.com]] rated him as the 36th best shooting guard in his class.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://michigan.scout.com/a.z?s=162&p=8&c=1&nid=3798656|title=Tim Hardaway|accessdate=2011-02-27|publisher=[[Scout.com]]}}</ref> He was not top-ranked by [[Rivals.com]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rivals.yahoo.com/basketballrecruiting/basketball/recruiting/player-Tim-Hardaway-70973;_ylt=AlwlcN3T.ka5q1OnnBO4Ut7SO5B4|title=Time Hardaway|accessdate=2011-02-27|publisher=[[Rivals.com]]}}</ref> Hardaway has played summer [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) basketball for both the South Florida Heat<ref name=THJsg/> and Chicago's Mac Irvin Fire, where he teamed with {{convert|7|ft|m|2|adj=on}} [[Meyers Leonard]] and [[McDonald's All-American]] [[Jereme Richmond]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/hoopsreport/2013/04/fire_wins_meanstreets_and_wolv.html|title=Mac Irvin Fire wins, Meanstreets and Wolves impress|accessdate=2013-04-12|date=2013-04-10|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=Henricksen, Joe}}</ref>
