==College==
===Freshman year===
Although Hardaway led the team in scoring in his first career game and the season opener with 19 points against {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=South Carolina Spartans|school=University of South Carolina Upstate|title=South Carolina Upstate}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=303170130|title=USC Upstate 35 (0-1, 0-1 away); Michigan 66 (1-0, 1-0 home)|accessdate=2011-02-28|date=2010-11-13|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> he was soon in a shooting slump that saw him shoot 4 for 30 on his [[field goal (basketball)|field goals]] in late November games against [[2010<U+2013>11 Syracuse Orange men's basketball team|Syracuse]] and {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=UTEP Miners|school=University of Texas at El Paso|title=UTEP}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/michigan-forward-tim-hardaway-jr-breaks-out-of-his-funk-and-jordan-morgans-foul-trouble/|title=Michigan forward Tim Hardaway Jr. breaks out of his funk and Jordan Morgan's foul trouble|accessdate=2011-02-28|date=2010-12-01|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref> These games marked the beginning of a slump during which he went 13 consecutive games without achieving a 50% [[field goal percentage]] and 19 games without exceeding that number.<ref name=TH1011gl>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/gamelog/_/id/51270/year/2011/tim-hardaway-jr|title=Tim Hardaway Jr. Game-by-Game Stats (2010-11)|accessdate=2011-11-26|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

[[File:20101223 Tim Hardaway, Jr..jpg|thumb|left|Hardaway shooting a [[free throw]] (12-23-2010)]]
Hardaway earned four Big Ten Freshman of the week awards.  On December 27, the [[Big Ten Conference]] named Hardaway co-freshman of the week along with [[Jared Sullinger]].<ref name=MaOSCWCH>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/122710aac.html|title=Michigan and Ohio State Claim Weekly Conference Honors: Michigan and Ohio State earn conference recognition|accessdate=2010-12-28|date=2010-12-27|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> On December 23, 2010, against {{cbb link|2010|sex=men|team=Bryant Bulldogs|school=Bryant University|title=Bryant University}}, [[2010<U+2013>11 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|the team]] tied its December 13, 2008 single-game school record of 16 [[three-point field goal]]s made,<ref name="All-Time Records">{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/mich/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/bkm-all-time-records|title=All-Time Records|accessdate=2011-01-16|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com|page=6}}</ref> and Hardaway was one of three Wolverines to make 4 three-point shots.<ref name="All-Time Records"/><ref name=BU7M8>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=303570130|title=Bryant U 71 (1-10, 0-1 NEC): Michigan 87 (10-2, 9-0 home)|accessdate=2011-02-03|date=2010-12-23|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> It was Hardaway's first 20-point game.<ref name=MaOSCWCH/> On February 14, Hardaway earned his second Big Ten Conference Freshman of the week recognition for his first career [[Double (basketball)#Double-double|double-double]] on February 9 against [[2010-11 Northwestern Wildcats men's basketball team|Northwestern]] (17 points and career-high 10 rebounds)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310400130|title=Northwestern  66 (14-9, 4-8 Big Ten); Michigan 75 (15-10, 5-7 Big Ten)|accessdate=2011-02-15|date=2011-02-09|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> and a career-high 26 points on February 12 against [[2010-11 Indiana Hoosiers men's basketball team|Indiana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310430130|title=Indiana  69 (12-14, 3-10 Big Ten); Michigan 73 (16-10, 6-7 Big Ten)|accessdate=2011-02-15|date=2011-02-12|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/021411aab.html|title=Wisconsin and Michigan Receive Men's Basketball Weekly Honors: Wisconsin's Jordan Taylor earns Player of the Week; Michigan's Tim Hardaway receives Freshman of the Week honors.|accessdate=2011-02-15|date=2011-02-14|publisher=[[Big Ten Conference]]}}</ref> The following week, Hardaway earned a third Big Ten Conference Freshman of the week award as he became the first Michigan freshman to score thirty points in a game in eight years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/022111aac.html|title=Purdue and Michigan Garner Weekly Basketball Awards: Purdue's E'Twaun Moore earns Player of the Week while Tim Hardaway Jr. was tabbed Freshman of the Week.|accessdate=2011-02-22|date=2011-02-21|publisher=[[Big Ten Conference]]}}</ref>  His thirty points came in a 75&ndash;72 February 19 [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] victory over Iowa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310502294|title=Michigan  75 (17-11, 7-8 Big Ten); Iowa 72 (10-17, 3-12 Big Ten)|accessdate=2011-02-22|date=2011-02-19|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> He had also scored 10 points and added 5 assists in a 54&ndash;52 loss to [[2010-11 Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball team|Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310470356|title=Michigan  52 (16-11, 6-8 Big Ten); Illinois 54 (17-9, 7-6 Big Ten)|accessdate=2011-02-22|date=2011-02-16|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On February 28, Hardaway earned his third consecutive and fourth overall Big Ten Conference Freshman of the week recognition.<ref name=PaMGCR>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/022811aaa.html|title=Purdue and Michigan Garner Conference Recognition: Purdue's JaJuan Johnson earns Player of the Week while Michigan's Tim Hardaway Jr. was tabbed Freshman of the Week.|accessdate=2011-02-28|date=2011-02-28|publisher=[[Big Ten Conference]]}}</ref>  During the week, Hardaway extended his double-digit scoring streak to eleven by posting 22 points against [[2010-11 Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball team|Minnesota]] on February 26 after scoring 16 against #12 [[2010-11 Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball team|Wisconsin]] on February 23.<ref name=PaMGCR/><ref name=M5W5>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310540130|title=(12) Wisconsin  53 (21-6, 11-4 Big Ten); Michigan 52 (17-12, 7-9 Big Ten)|accessdate=2011-02-28|date=2011-02-23|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref name=M7M6>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=310570135|title=Michigan  70 (18-12, 8-9 Big Ten); Minnesota 63 (17-11, 6-10 Big Ten)|accessdate=2011-02-28|date=2011-02-26|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>  For the week, he shot 9 for 15 on his three-point shots.<ref name=M5W5/><ref name=M7M6/>

As a result of the three consecutive freshman of the week performances and a final week in which he scored 20 in the team's only game, he averaged 20.1 points during the final 7 games of the regular season while the team won six of its final eight,<ref name=TH1011gl/> which enabled it to finish tied for fourth for the conference standings and earn the fourth seed in the [[2011 Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030611aac.html|title=Big Ten Announces Bracket For 2011 Men's Basketball Tournament: Ohio State earns No. 1 seed for fifth time in tournament history|accessdate=2011-03-07|date=2011-03-06|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> He led the team in scoring during the 18-game conference schedule of the [[2010<U+2013>11 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season]], edging out teammate [[Darius Morris]] by a 268&ndash;263 (14.9&ndash;14.6 points per game) margin. He also led the team in [[steal (basketball)|steals]] (1.17/game), [[free throw percentage]] (71.2%, min 2.0 made/game), three point shooting percentage (44.2%, min 1.0 made/game), and three-point shots made per game (2.56) over the course of the conference schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/stats/2010-2011/confonly.html|title=2010-11 Big Ten Conference: CONFERENCE BASKETBALL STATISTICS|accessdate=2011-03-05|date=2011-03-07|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Following the Big Ten Conference season, Hardaway was an honorable mention All-Big Ten selection by both the coaches and the media.  Hardaway was also one of two unanimous All-Freshman team selections by the coaches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigtennetwork.com/dpp/sports/basketball-mens/big-ten-releases-all-big-ten-teams-201137|title=Big Ten Releases All-Big Ten Teams: Purdue's Johnson named Player of the Year|accessdate=2011-03-08|date=2011-03-07|publisher=[[Big Ten Network]]}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He was one of 21 players selected to the 2011 [[Collegeinsider.com]] Freshmen All-America selection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collegeinsider.com/awards/2011_freshmen.html|title=The 2011 Freshmen All-America team |accessdate=2011-04-06|date=2011-03-25|publisher=[[Collegeinsider.com]]}}</ref>

In the semifinals of the 2011 Big Ten Tournament against [[2010-11 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]], he set the Michigan freshman single-season three-point shots made record of 74.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/031211aad.html|title=Ohio State-Michigan Postgame Notes|accessdate=2011-03-14|date=2011-03-13|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>  For the season, Hardaway led the team in three-point shots made per game and [[free throw percentage]] (among qualifying players).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/stats/2010-2011/confldrs.html|title=2010-11 Big Ten Conference: Conference Basketball Statistics|accessdate=2011-03-21|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> He finished the season with 16 consecutive double digit scoring efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/032011aaf.html|title=Postgame Notes: #3 Duke 73, Michigan 71|accessdate=2011-03-20|date=2011-03-20|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref>

Following the season he was invited to the June 17 &mdash; June 24, 2011 17-man tryouts for the 12-man [[FIBA Under-19 World Championship]] team by [[USA Basketball]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5zORTWpbi|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20110512/SPORTS08/110512030/Keith-Appling-Tim-Hardaway-Jr-invited-USA-Basketball-U-19-tryouts|title=Keith Appling, Tim Hardaway Jr. invited to USA Basketball U-19 tryouts|accessdate=2011-06-12|archivedate=2011-06-12|date=2011-05-12|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Snyder, Mark}}</ref> The 12 selected players competed as Team USA in the [[2011 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|2011 FIBA U19 World Championships]] in Latvia from June 30 &mdash; July 10, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/michigan-guard-tim-hardaway-jr-prepares-for-u-19-usa-basketball-tryouts/|title=Michigan guard Tim Hardaway Jr. prepares for U-19 USA Basketball tryouts|accessdate=2011-06-12|date=2011-06-12|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Rothstein, Micheal}}</ref> He was selected to the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/tim-hardaway-jr-makes-12-man-usa-u19-roster-will-play-in-europe/|title=Tim Hardaway Jr. makes 12-man USA U19 roster, will play in Europe|accessdate=2011-06-26|date=2011-06-24|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/oly/olybb/news/story?id=6696456|title=One prep player on U.S. U-19 team|accessdate=2011-06-26|date=2011-06-23|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

