[[CBS Sports]] listed him as the 35th best player in its preseason top 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/storylist/20512719/2/2012-13-college-basketball-previews/cbssportscoms-top-100-players|title=CBSSports.com's Top 100 Players|accessdate=2012-10-09|date=2012-10-08|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]}}</ref> He was a preseason [[John R. Wooden Award]] top 50 selection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/collegebasketballnation/post/_/id/66564/wooden-award-preseason-top-50-unveiled|title=Wooden Award preseason top 50 unveiled|accessdate=2012-11-08|date=2012-11-08|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Medcalf, Myron}}</ref> During the season, [[Trey Burke]] and Hardaway were constantly referred to as the best backcourt in college basketball. The praise came from a variety of leading media outlets such as [[FOX Sports]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ca.msn.com/photos/college-basketball-player-of-the-year-watch?page=3|title=College basketball: Player of the Year Watch: Trey Burke, Michigan|accessdate=2013-02-22|date=2012-12-05|publisher=[[FOX Sports]]}}</ref> [[ESPN]] [[color commentator]] [[Dick Vitale]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww.annarbor.com/sports/um-basketball/who-was-mvp-tim-hardaway-jr-or-trey-burke-in-michigans-76-74-overtime-win-over-ohio-state/|title=with poll: Who was MVP, Tim Hardaway Jr. or Trey Burke, in Michigan's 76-74 overtime win over Ohio State?|accessdate=2013-02-22|date=2013-02-05|work=[[AnnArbor.com]]|author=Cunningham, Pete}}</ref> [[ESPN]] journalists such as [[Miles Simon]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insider.espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/8873717/why-michigan-wolverines-backcourt-best-nation-college-basketball|title=Michigan's elite backcourt: Why Wolverines' guard play is nation's best, and what it means for title hopes|accessdate=2013-02-22|date=2013-01-24|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Simon, Miles}}</ref> ''[[Bleacher Report]]'' columnist Zach Dirlam (who included backcourt depth provided by [[Nik Stauskas]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1505099-michigan-basketball-where-does-wolverines-backcourt-rank-among-nations-best|title=Michigan Basketball: Where Does Wolverines' Backcourt Rank Among Nation's Best?|accessdate=2013-02-22|date=2013-01-26|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|author=Simon, Miles}}</ref> as well as lots of local press.
[[File:20130103 Tim Hardaway, Jr dunk.jpg|thumb|upright|Hardaway [[slam dunk|dunking]] for the [[2012<U+2013>13 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2012<U+2013>13 Wolverines]] in the January 3 [[2012<U+2013>13 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|2012<U+2013>13 Big Ten Conference season]] opener against [[2012<U+2013>13 Northwestern Wildcats men's basketball team|Northwestern]] at [[Welsh-Ryan Arena]]]]
Hardaway began the season with a double-double by scoring 25 points (including 5-for-5 three point shooting) and adding 10 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=323140130|title=Slippery Rock 62; (5) Michigan 100 (1-0, 1-0 home)|accessdate=2012-11-10|date=2012-11-09|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> His fourth career double-double earned him his second Big Ten Player of the Week award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/111212aaa.html|title=Indiana and Michigan Earn Big Ten Weekly Awards: Michigan's Hardaway named Player of the Week; Hoosiers' Ferrell tabbed Freshman of the Week |accessdate=2012-11-12|date=2012-11-02|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=BigTen.org}}</ref> Hardaway earned the [[NIT Season Tip-Off]] MVP with 39 points total in the November 21 semifinal and November 23 final against [[2012<U+2013>13 Pittsburgh Panthers men's basketball team|Pittsburgh]] and [[2012<U+2013>13 Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball team|Kansas State]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/112312aaa.html|title=Hardaway's MVP Effort Leads U-M to First NIT Season Tip-Off Title|accessdate=2012-11-24|date=2012-11-23|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=323280130|title=Michigan shrugs off Kansas State to win NIT Season Tip-off|accessdate=2012-11-24|date=2012-11-23|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=323260221|title=No. 4 Michigan stifles Pittsburgh to reach NIT Season Tipoff final|accessdate=2012-11-24|date=2012-11-21|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On December 20, he posted a career-high 7 assists against [[2012<U+2013>13 Eastern Michigan Eagles men's basketball team|Eastern Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=323550130|title=Tim Hardaway Jr., No. 2 Michigan rout Eastern Michigan|accessdate=2012-12-21|date=2012-12-20|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/122012aad.html|title=Postgame Notes: #2 Michigan 93, Eastern Michigan 54|accessdate=2012-12-21|date=2012-12-20|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> Hardaway suffered an ankle injury that caused him to miss the December 29 game against [[2012<U+2013>13 Central Michigan Chippewas men's basketball team|Central Michigan]] and that broke his 81 consecutive games played streak that went back to the beginning of his Michigan career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/8791413/tim-hardaway-jr-michigan-wolverines-saturday-vs-central-michigan-chippewas|title=Tim Hardaway Jr. (ankle) sits out|accessdate=2012-12-30|date=2012-12-29|author=Rothstein, Michael|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> In the subsequent game on January 3, he returned to the lineup for the [[2012<U+2013>13 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season]] opener against [[2012<U+2013>13 Northwestern Wildcats men's basketball team|Northwestern]] with 21 points and four assists in a 94&ndash;66 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330030077|title=Trey Burke, Tim Hardaway Jr. spark No. 2 Michigan's rout|accessdate=2013-01-05|date=2013-01-03|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Two games later on January 9, he tied a career high with 11 rebounds and added 15 points for his fifth career double-double.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/010913aae.html|title=Postgame Notes: #2 Michigan 62, Nebraska 47|accessdate=2013-01-11|date=2013-01-09|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330090130|title=No. 2 Michigan shakes off Nebraska, moves to 16-0|accessdate=2013-01-11|date=2013-01-09|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> On January 17, Michigan defeated [[2012<U+2013>13 Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball team|Minnesota]] (#9 AP/#12 Coaches) at [[Williams Arena]], marking the first time Michigan defeated a top-10 team on the road since a December 6, 1996 victory by the [[1996<U+2013>97 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1996<U+2013>97 team]] over [[1996<U+2013>97 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330170135|title=Tim Hardaway Jr., No. 5 Michigan knock off No. 9 Minnesota|accessdate=2013-01-18|date=2013-01-17|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Hardaway earned a second Big Ten Player of the Week Award following a  21-points performance on 7-for-8 shooting (4-for-5 three-point shot) with 5 rebounds, 3 assists, 3 steals and 2 blocks.<ref name="bigten8">{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/012113aaa.html|title=Michigan and Nebraska Claim Weekly Awards|accessdate=2013-01-21|date=2013-01-21|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=BigTen.org}}</ref> On January 28, Michigan was ranked number one in the [[AP Poll]] with 51 of the 65 first place votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/8890627/michigan-wolverines-no-1-first-time-fab-5-1992|title=Michigan moves to No. 1 in AP poll|accessdate=2013-01-28|date=2013-01-28|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> It marked the first time Michigan ranked atop the AP Poll since the [[Fab Five (University of Michigan)|Fab Five]] [[1992<U+2013>93 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|1992<U+2013>93 team]] did so on December 5, 1992.<ref name=PN#M7I6>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/012713aaa.html|title=Postgame Notes: #2 Michigan 74, Illinois 60|accessdate=2013-01-28|date=2013-01-28|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> On February 5, Hardaway tallied a career high 6 three-point shots, including three on consecutive possessions to give Michigan its first lead of the second half in an [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] victory against [[2012<U+2013>13 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=330360130|title=(10) Ohio St 74 (17-5, 7-3 Big Ten); (3) Michigan 76 (21-2, 8-2 Big Ten)|accessdate=2013-02-06|date=2013-02-05|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/020613aah.html|title=Postgame Notes: #3 Michigan 76, #10 Ohio State 74 (OT)|accessdate=2013-02-06|date=2013-02-06|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref>  

[[File:20130323 Tim Hardaway Jr.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Hardaway during the [[2013 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2013 NCAA Tournament]]]]
Prior to the [[2013 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]], Jeff Goodman of [[CBSSports.com]] named Michigan with Hardaway first among tournament teams in terms of having the most future [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] talent on its roster (in the absence of [[2012<U+2013>13 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]] who was relegated to the [[2013 National Invitation Tournament]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/blog/eye-on-college-basketball/21917791/ncaa-tournament-10-teams-with-the-most-future-nba-talent|title=NCAA tournament: 10 teams with the most future NBA talent|accessdate=2013-03-21|date=2013-03-20|publisher=[[CBSSports.com]]|author=Goodman, Jeff}}</ref> As a number four seed, Michigan defeated its first NCAA tournament opponent, [[2012<U+2013>13 South Dakota State Jackrabbits men's basketball team |South Dakota State]], 71&ndash;56.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=330800130|title=Glenn Robinson III leads No. 4 Michigan past No.13 South Dakota State|accessdate=2013-03-22|date=2013-03-21|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> Hardaway established a new NCAA tournament career-high with 21 points. The 27th victory of the season gave the team its most wins in 20 years and matched head coach [[John Beilein]]'s career high.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/032113aak.html|title=Postgame Notes: #10 Michigan 71, South Dakota State 56|accessdate=2013-03-22|date=2013-03-21|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref>  In the regional finals on March 31 against [[2012<U+2013>13 Florida Gators men's basketball team|Florida]], freshman [[Nik Stauskas]] made all 6 of his three-point shot attempts, pushing his single-season total to 79 and surpassing Hardaway's single-season freshman school record.<ref name=PNM7F5>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/recaps/033113aap.html|title=Postgame Notes: #10 Michigan 79, #14 Florida 59|accessdate=2013-03-31|date=2013-03-31|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> Following the regional championship postgame prayer and with Mrs. Beilein's consent, Hardaway and [[Mitch McGary]] gave 
head coach [[John Beilein]] a [[gatorade shower]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/tournament/2013/story/_/id/9118867/2013-ncaa-tournament-michigan-wolverines-beat-florida-roll-final-four|title=Michigan crushes UF to reach Atlanta|accessdate=2013-04-01|date=2013-04-01|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> In the April 6 national semifinal against [[2012<U+2013>13 Syracuse Orange men's basketball team|Syracuse]], Hardaway contributed a team-high 13 points, 6 rebounds and 5 assists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=330960130|title=(4) Syracuse 56 (30-10, 11-7 Big East); (4) Michigan 61 (31-7, 12-6 Big Ten)|accessdate=2013-04-07|date=2013-04-06|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

====Honors and awards====
Following the [[2012<U+2013>13 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|2012<U+2013>13 Big Ten season]] he was a 1st team All-Big Ten selection by the coaches and a 2nd team second team selection by the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigten.org/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/031113aaf.html|title=Big Ten Announces 2013 Men's Basketball Postseason Honors|accessdate=2013-03-12|date=2013-03-11|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=BigTen.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/big10/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/2012-13/misc_non_event/2013AllBigTen.pdf|title=2012-13 All-Big Ten Men<U+2019>s Basketball Team|accessdate=2013-03-12|date=2013-03-11|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=BigTen.org}}</ref>  On March&nbsp;12, the [[United States Basketball Writers Association|U.S. Basketball Writers Association]] named Hardaway to its 2012<U+2013>13 Men's All-District V (OH, IN, IL, MI, MN, WI) Team, based upon voting from its national membership.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bigten.org/blog/2013/03/nine-big-ten-standouts-named-to-usbwa-all-district-teams.html| work=BigTen.org| publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]| title=Nine Big Ten Standouts Named To USBWA All-District Teams| accessdate=2013-03-13|date=2013-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.sportswriters.net/usbwa/news/2013/alldistrict130312.html| publisher=[[United States Basketball Writers Association]]| title=USBWA Names Men's All-District Teams| accessdate=2013-03-13|date=2013-03-12}}</ref>  He was named to the  [[National Association of Basketball Coaches]] Division&nbsp;I All<U+2010>District 7 first team on March 26, as selected and voted on by member coaches of the NABC, making him eligible for the State Farm Coaches<U+2019> Division&nbsp;I All-America team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nabc.com/awards/all_district/FINAL-2012-13NABC-D1-ALL-DISTRICT-TEAMS-5.pdf|title=National Association of Basketball Coaches Announces 2012-13 Division I All-District Teams|accessdate=2013-05-18|date=2013-03-26|publisher=[[National Association of Basketball Coaches]]}}</ref>

==Pro career==
===2013 NBA Draft===
At 12:21 PM ET on April 4, [[Forbes]] sports business reporter Darren Heitner tweeted that Hardaway and teammate Burke would declare for the [[2013 NBA Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20130404/SPORTS06/130404032/michigan-basketball-nba-draft-trey-burke-tim-hardaway-jr-|title=Report: Tim Hardaway Jr., Trey Burke will leave Michigan early; parents deny it|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Snyder, Mark|accessdate=2013-04-04|date=2013-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DarrenHeitner/status/319847105516679168|title=<U+200F>@DarrenHeitner Status update|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Heitner, Darren|accessdate=2013-04-04|date=2013-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DarrenHeitner/status/319849471636811776|title=<U+200F>@DarrenHeitner Status update|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Heitner, Darren|accessdate=2013-04-04|date=2013-04-04}}</ref> At 2:23 PM, Heitner tweeted that Hardaway, Sr. said his son was undecided.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DarrenHeitner/status/319877834996850688|title=<U+200F>@DarrenHeitner Status update|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Heitner, Darren|accessdate=2013-04-04|date=2013-04-04}}</ref> On April 9 before boarding the airplane to return from the NCAA Final Four, Beilein met with Burke, Hardaway, Robinson and McGary to direct them to seek the advice of the NBA advisory committee. The draft board has until April 15 to develop each individual report and the players have until April 28 to enter the draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2013/04/michigan_nba_prospects_seeking.html|title=Michigan's NBA prospects seeking advice from draft board, John Beilein being 'proactive' with process|accessdate=2013-04-11|date=2013-04-11|work=MLive.com|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> On April 12, ESPN journalist Myron Medcalf predicted Hardaway would enter the draft noting that the 2014 draft was likely to be wing-heavy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/9163283/a-look-college-underclassmen-decided-undecided-nba-draft-college-basketball|title=Underclassmen: To go or not to go?|accessdate=2013-04-12|date=2013-04-12|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Medcalf, Myron}}</ref> On April 17, Hardaway declared for the NBA Draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/draft2013/story/_/id/9183145/nba-draft-2013-tim-hardaway-jr-michigan-wolverines-enter-nba-draft|title=Tim Hardaway Jr. to enter draft |accessdate=2013-04-19|date=2013-04-17|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Rothstein, Michael}}</ref> Hardaway signed with [[sports agent]] Mark Bartelstein, the father of a former Michigan teammate who represents 37 NBA players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20130513/SPORTS06/305130076/nba-draft-michigan-basketball-tim-hardaway-jr|title=Tim Hardaway Jr. doesn't regret his 'sacrificial' role at Michigan|accessdate=2013-05-14|date=2013-05-13|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Snyder, Mark}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2013/05/tim_hardaway_jr_signs_with_age.html|title=Tim Hardaway Jr. signs with agent Mark Bartelstein, father of ex-Michigan teammate Josh Bartelstein|accessdate=2013-05-14|date=2013-05-02|publisher=MLive.com|author=Baumgardner, Nick}}</ref> Hardaway was one of 60 players invited to the NBA Draft Combine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://probasketballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/05/13/complete-nba-draft-combine-invite-list/|title=Complete NBA Draft Combine invite list|accessdate=2013-05-14|date=2013-05-02|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|author=Helin, Kurt}}</ref> At the combine, Hardaway strengthened his draft stock with his physical measurements and his athletic results.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1643015-nba-draft-combine-results-2013-winners-and-losers-from-chicago/page/6|title=NBA Draft Combine Results 2013: Winners and Losers From Chicago: Winner: Tim Hardaway Jr., Michigan|accessdate=2013-05-19|date=2013-05-17|work=[[Bleacher Report]]|author=Wasserman, Jonathan}}</ref>

Hardaway was drafted 24th by the [[New York Knicks]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nba.si.com/2013/06/27/tim-hardaway-jr-nba-draft-2013/|title=Tim Hardaway Jr. selected No. 24 by Knicks in NBA draft|accessdate=2013-06-28|date=2013-06-27|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Mahoney, Rob}}</ref> who had entered draft day with only two guards under contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/28/sports/basketball/knicks-needing-help-at-guard-get-hardaway.html?_r=0|title=Needing Help at Guard, Knicks Pick Hardaway|accessdate=2013-06-29|date=2013-06-27|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Taylor, Nate}}</ref> Burke and Hardaway became the first Michigan duo selected in the first round since [[Juwan Howard]] and [[Jalen Rose]] in the [[1994 NBA Draft]]. Hardaway joined his father (14th in [[1989 NBA Draft]]) as a first round selection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/062613aaa.html|title=Burke Chosen No. 9, Traded to Utah; Hardaway Taken by Knicks|accessdate=2013-06-28|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/062713aan.html|title=Burke, Hardaway Selected in First Round of NBA Draft|accessdate=2013-06-28|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> 

===New York Knicks===
Hardaway tweeted that he chose to wear jersey number 5 because that was his father's number as a rookie.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/t_hard10/status/353505173370449920|title=@t_hard10 status|accessdate=2013-07-06|date=2013-07-06|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Hardaway, Tim Jr.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2013/07/08/tim-hardaway-jr-agrees-to-a-4-year-contract-with-knicks/|title=Tim Hardaway Jr. Agrees To A 4-Year Contract With Knicks: Hardaway Jr. Was Drafted 24th Overall By The Knicks|accessdate=2013-07-09|publisher=[[CBS New York]]}}</ref> On July 8, The Knicks announced that Hardaway signed a 4-year $6.1 million contract, clearing the way for him to play in the July 12&ndash;22 [[Las Vegas Summer League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/general/blog/eye-on-sports/22685376/knicks-sign-first-round-pick-tim-hardaway-jr|title=Knicks sign first-round pick Tim Hardaway Jr.|accessdate=2013-07-09|date=2013-07-08|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|author=Hilbert, Evan}}</ref> In the second game of the summer league, he suffered a bruised wrist. At the time,  ESPNNewYork.com journalist Jared Zwerling noted that Hardaway had shown strong half court offensive skills, such as the ability to drive off of a [[pick and roll]] and an explosive first step, but that  his lateral defensive skills needed development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-york/knicks/post/_/id/46964/notes-hardaway-jr-suffers-bruised-left-wrist|title=Notes: Hardaway Jr. suffers bruised wrist|accessdate=2013-07-16|date=2013-07-14|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Zwerling, Jared}}</ref>

==Personal==
He has a sister named Nia<ref name=TSoaN/>, a dog named Tito, and is the son of five-time NBA All-Star [[Tim Hardaway]]. During the 2012&ndash;13 season Hardaway memorialized deceased friends on his left shoe and deceased family members on his right shoe.<ref name=THJsg>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/tournament/2013/story/_/id/9132806/2013-final-four-tim-hardaway-jr-writes-shoes-honor-loved-ones-passed-away|title=Tim Hardaway Jr.'s symbolic gesture: Writing on shoes is his way to honor loved ones who have passed|accessdate=2013-04-08|date=2013-04-04|author=Rothstein, Michael|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>

